{
  "text": "Pharmacological blockade of DOR systemically by NTI, naltriben or SORI-9409 decreased voluntary ethanol consumption [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ) and also cue-mediated drug seeking [CITATION_3] . Those studies suggested that DOR are likely involved in both rewarding properties of alcohol and learning processes responsible for the context-drug consumption association. Local administration of DOR antagonists into the ventral tegmental area (VTA) [CITATION_4] , the dorsal striatum [CITATION_5] or the central nucleus of the amygdala (Bie et al., 2009 ) also disrupted ethanol selfadministration or ethanol-induced CPP. In accordance, systemic or local administration (dorsal striatum and paraventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus) of DOR agonists stimulated ethanol SA (Barson et al., 2010; [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Therefore, pharmacology approaches concur to indicate that DOR activation at several brain sites, and overall, facilitates ethanol drinking in rodents.",
  "correct_citation": {
